subSection.paragraph:
Nowadays, 
in silico
methods have become noticeable during the development of novel drugs, and quantitative-structure activity relationship (QSAR) studies have been employed to identify important chemical features and consequently propose descriptors related with the respective biological activity, thus assisting in the discovery of novel potential lead compounds (
Danishuddin and Khan, 2016
; 
Martinez et al., 2017
). In fact, QSAR has been considered an important tool in the rational development and discovery of new drugs (
Danishuddin and Khan, 2016
; 
Martinez et al., 2017
).

As established in the scientific literature, microbial transformation is an area of great interest to the pharmaceutical and chemical industries, once it allows for the production of derivatives that are difficult to obtain by organic synthesis (
dos Santos et al., 2018
; 
Parshikov and Sutherland, 2014
). Biotransformation studies of natural products using 

Aspergillus
species

are commonly found in the scientific literature and hydroxylation is the major reaction produced by these microorganisms (
Parshikov and Sutherland, 2014
; 
Porto et al., 2013
; 
Severiano et al., 2013
).

Aiming to obtain a rich fraction of acid diterpenes from microbial transformation extract, AtE (
2.24 g
) was firstly submitted to an acidbase extraction, according to the methodology previously described by 
Carman (1964)
. The resulting organic phase from this procedure (AtEO; 
1.53 g
) was chromatographed over silica gel 60 
H
(Merck, art.7736) using VLC with increasing amounts of ethyl acetate in hexanes as eluent. This procedure furnished seven fractions (300 mL each): AtEO1 (12.0 mg; hexanes), AtEO2 (23.0 mg; 20% ethyl acetate), AtEO3 (
836.1 mg
; 40% ethyl acetate), AtEO4 (
96.2 mg
; 60% ethyl acetate), AtEO5 (
81.3 mg
; 80% ethyl acetate), AtEO6 (
45.1 mg
; ethyl acetate) and AtEO7 (
125.3 mg
; MeOH). AtEO3 was initially partitioned by classic chromatography (CC) using an isocratic hexanes/EtOAc 8:2 mobile phase; ten new fractions were obtained (AtEO3.1- AtEO3.10). Diterpene 
ent
-7α-hydroxy-kaur-16-en-19-oic acid (compound 
2
; 
Fig. 1
; 
256.4 mg
) was identified from AtEO3.5. TLC analysis (Whatman, 250.0 μm layer) of AtEO3.7 revealed a main spot that was purified by flash chromatography (hexanes/ethyl acetate/CHCl3 5:2:3), furnishing the derivative 
ent
-15β-hydroxy-kaur-16-en-19-oic acid (compound 
3
; 
Fig. 1
; 
39.7 mg
). AtEO4 and AtEO5 were combined on the basis of their quite similar TLC profile and designated AtEO4 (
177.5 mg
). This new fraction was first partitioned by CC (hexanes/ethyl acetate/CHCl3 4:3:3), leading to six additional fractions (AtEO4.1–AtEO4.6). Diterpene 
ent
-7α,11β-dihydroxy-kaur-16-en-19-oic acid (compound 
5
; 
Fig. 1
; 
12.1 mg
) was obtained from fraction AtEO4.6 after purification performed by washing with cold 
CH
2Cl2. Finally, analysis of AtEO7 by TLC revealed that the main metabolite present in this fraction afforded an extensive tail, which is a characteristic of compounds containing COOH groups in their structure. Aiming to facilitate its isolation, fraction AtEO7 was treated with ethereal diazomethane (Batista et al., 2007), and diterpene methyl 
ent
-7α,16β-dihydroxy-kaur-19-oate was later purified by CC (hexanes/ethyl acetate 1:1) as its methyl ester derivative (compound 
4
; 
Fig. 1
; 
25.2 mg
). This reaction was also performed with diterpene 
2
(50.0 mg) and its respective methyl ester (compound 
6
; 
Fig. 1
; 
34.6 mg
) was obtained after purification by CC (hexanes/ethyl acetate 8:2).
